  The script also bumped QTDIR to match the 6.9.0 path now in your CMakeLists. Set SKIP_NOTARIZE=1 for fast iteration locally       
  without going through Apple.
                                                                                                                                    
  One-time setup before you run it                                                                                                  
  
  You need to give notarytool a stored credential so the script can submit unattended. From your Mac:                               
                                                            
  xcrun notarytool store-credentials AC_PASSWORD \                                                                                  
      --apple-id "braernoch@gmail.com" \                                                                                            
      --team-id "39683CAT84" \                                                                                                      
      --password "<APP-SPECIFIC PASSWORD>"                                                                                          
                                                                                                                                    
  The app-specific password is not your Apple ID password — generate one at https://appleid.apple.com → Sign-In and Security →      
  App-Specific Passwords. Once stored, the keychain holds it under the name AC_PASSWORD, and the script reuses it on every run.
                                                                                                                                    
  Verify it actually worked                                                                                                         
  
  After running the install, on a different Mac (or simulating one):                                                                
                                                            
  # Simulate "downloaded from internet" quarantine (Gatekeeper's gate)                                                              
  xattr -w com.apple.quarantine "0083;00000000;Safari;" atomix.app                                                                  
  # Should print: atomix.app: accepted    source=Notarized Developer ID                                                             
  spctl -a -vvv -t exec atomix.app                                                                                                  
                                                                                                                                    
  If spctl says "accepted, source=Notarized Developer ID," it'll launch on any Mac without xattr workarounds. If it says            
  "source=Developer ID" only (no "Notarized"), stapling didn't happen.
                                                                                                                                    
  Likely first-run hiccups                                  

  - No "Developer ID Application" cert in keychain. Check with security find-identity -v -p codesigning. If it's missing, you need  
  to create one in your dev account → Certificates, ID & Profiles → "+" → "Developer ID Application," download, and double-click the
   .cer. (Apple Development ≠ Developer ID Application — they're separate cert types.)                                              
  - Notarization rejection because --timestamp couldn't reach Apple's TSA, or because some dylib was skipped. The submission ID
  prints to stdout; fetch the log with xcrun notarytool log <id> --keychain-profile AC_PASSWORD. The log will name the offending    
  file.
  - App still won't open after notarization. Almost always means the hardened runtime is killing it because something needs an      
  entitlement we didn't grant. Run the app from Console.app or Console and look for "EXC_BAD_ACCESS / KERN_PROTECTION_FAILURE" or   
  "Library Validation failed" — if it's the latter, library-validation is already disabled, so it's something else. Send me the
  crash log and I'll narrow it down.
  